'''Yokota Shrine''' (よこたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Sōja|Q873536|WD=Q873536|1=Sōja}}, {{ill|lt=Okayama Prefecture|Q132936|WD=Q132936|1=Okayama Prefecture}}. It is one of the seven shrines in Sōja counted as Engishiki-listed shrines, being a {{ill|lt=Engishiki-listed shrine|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} (small) of {{ill|lt=Shimomichi District|Q10868734|WD=Q10868734|1=Katō district}}, {{ill|lt=Bitchū Province|Q1047514|WD=Q1047514|1=Bitchū Province}}. It stands in the Kushiro area in western Sōja, on the southern foot of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Masakiyama|1=UNKNOWN}}, and its {{ill|lt=ujiko|Q125562175|WD=Q125562175|1=Ujiko}} area covers central and northwestern parts of that district (koaza names: Bessho, Yokota, Origami, Yamaguchi, Shimizu, Oshikida). Former rank was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q10940685|lt=Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto|1=Ame no Hohi}} and {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}, with divine virtues such as academic success and wish fulfillment.

=== Origin ===
Founding era is unknown. One tradition says that when {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|WD=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}} stayed at a temporary palace here, {{ill|lt=Prince Ōtomo|Q357242|WD=Q357242|lt=Prince Ōtomo|1=Emperor Kōbun}} (son of {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenji|Q314802|WD=Q314802|1=Emperor Tenji}}) attacked with a great army to overthrow him. The emperor purified himself, worshiped heaven and earth deities, prayed for victory, defeated Prince Ōtomo's army, then built and revered a small shrine, which became Yokota Shrine<ref>'{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha Chōsa Hōkoku|1=UNKNOWN}}' quoting 'Kibi District Shrine Record.'</ref>.

According to a precinct {{ill|lt=stone monument|Q178743|WD=Q178743|1=Stele}} (built {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} 3 / {{ill|lt=1836|Q7601|WD=Q7601|1=1836}}) and other materials, the shrine declined once in the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|WD=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}}, then was revived in {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 13 ({{ill|lt=1585|Q6736|WD=Q6736|1=1585}}) as '''Tenjingū'''.

Later it was redeveloped between around {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 10 ({{ill|lt=1827|Q7008|WD=Q7008|1=1827}}) and Tenpō 7 (1836), and renamed again as '''Yokota Shrine'''. The current buildings are from around that period.

Formerly, {{ill|lt=Shōrinzan Shōfuku-ji (Sōja)|UNKNOWN|lt=Shōrinzan Shōfuku-ji}} in Bessho, west of the shrine site, served as the shrine's {{ill|lt=jingūji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}.

=== Festivals ===
*{{ill|lt=April 29|Q2535|WD=Q2535|1=April 29}} - Spring Festival
*{{ill|lt=August 4|Q2784|WD=Q2784|1=August 4}} - Summer Festival
*{{ill|lt=October 21|Q2960|WD=Q2960|1=October 21}} and {{ill|lt=October 22|Q2957|WD=Q2957|lt=22|1=October 22}} - Autumn Festival (with dedication of Bitchū Kagura)
Three festivals are held yearly (spring, summer, autumn); the autumn one is especially large, and {{ill|lt=Bitchū Kagura|Q11387313|WD=Q11387313|1=Bichu Kagura}} is dedicated in the {{ill|lt=kaguraden|Q94498|WD=Q94498|1=Kagura-den}} described below.

=== Shrine buildings ===
Current shrine buildings were completed around {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 10. The honden is 1-ken wide and 2-ken deep, {{ill|lt=irimoya-zukuri|Q855025|WD=Q855025|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}}, hira-iri. A southern {{ill|lt=corridor|Q106426877|WD=Q106426877|1=corridor}} links it to the {{ill|lt=haiden|Q3125745|WD=Q3125745|1=Haiden (Shinto)}}. Corridors extend east, west, and south from the haiden; especially the south corridor is long, and from above the complex appears in a distinct cross-like plan. West of the haiden is the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shamusho|1=UNKNOWN}}, east is Tenjingū enshrining Sugawara no Michizane, and at the end of the southern corridor stands a zuijin gate.

=== Precinct ===
Unusually for a shrine, it has a {{ill|lt=bell tower|Q1363585|WD=Q1363585|1=Shōrō}}. A kaguraden is also built on the south side of the precinct. Many small precinct shrines are enshrined within the grounds.

=== Access ===
From {{ill|lt=Sōja Station|Q844657|WD=Q844657|1=Sōja Station}} on JR {{ill|lt=Hakubi Line|Q844666|WD=Q844666|1=Hakubi Line}}, JR {{ill|lt=Kibi Line|Q844682|WD=Q844682|1=Kibi Line}}, or {{ill|lt=Ibara Railway|Q11373397|WD=Q11373397|1=Ibara Railway}}, take a {{ill|lt=Chūtetsu Bus|Q11367772|WD=Q11367772|1=Chutetsu Bus}} bound for {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Niimoto|1=UNKNOWN}}; get off at Yokota stop and walk about 3 minutes.

